
```
REGULAR TASKS DONE USING ANSIBLE IN PRODUCTION

=========================================================
1) SERVER PROVISIONING
=========================================================

- Install required packages (nginx, apache, docker, java, python)
- Create users and groups
- Configure sudo access
- Set timezone and hostname
- Configure SSH settings
- Install security updates

Example:
- Install nginx
- Create deployment user
- Disable root SSH login

=========================================================
2) APPLICATION DEPLOYMENT
=========================================================

- Pull code from Git
- Install dependencies
- Configure environment variables
- Restart services
- Deploy WAR/JAR files
- Deploy Docker containers

Example:
- Copy application files to /opt/app
- Restart systemd service
- Run database migrations

=========================================================
3) CONFIGURATION MANAGEMENT
=========================================================

- Manage config files (/etc/nginx/nginx.conf)
- Update application properties
- Modify system configuration
- Maintain consistent setup across 100+ servers

Ensures:
All servers have identical configuration.

=========================================================
4) SERVICE MANAGEMENT
=========================================================

- Start services
- Stop services
- Restart services
- Enable services at boot

Example:
- Restart nginx after config change
- Enable docker service

=========================================================
5) SECURITY HARDENING
=========================================================

- Disable root login
- Enforce password policies
- Install security patches
- Configure firewall (ufw, iptables)
- Rotate SSH keys

=========================================================
6) DATABASE MANAGEMENT
=========================================================

- Install MySQL/PostgreSQL
- Create databases
- Create DB users
- Backup databases
- Restore backups

=========================================================
7) LOG MANAGEMENT
=========================================================

- Configure log rotation
- Install monitoring agents
- Ship logs to ELK / Splunk
- Clean old log files

=========================================================
8) CLOUD AUTOMATION
=========================================================

- Launch EC2 instances
- Attach EBS volumes
- Create S3 buckets
- Configure Load Balancers
- Manage security groups

(Using collections like amazon.aws)

=========================================================
9) PATCH MANAGEMENT
=========================================================

- Run OS updates on all servers
- Reboot machines if required
- Ensure zero downtime using rolling updates

=========================================================
10) MULTI-SERVER ORCHESTRATION
=========================================================

Example production scenario:

Step 1: Stop application servers
Step 2: Deploy new version
Step 3: Run DB migration
Step 4: Start application
Step 5: Verify health check

All automated with one playbook.

=========================================================
REAL PRODUCTION FLOW
=========================================================

Developer pushes code
        ↓
CI/CD pipeline triggers
        ↓
Ansible runs playbook
        ↓
Application deployed on 10+ servers
        ↓
Load balancer routes traffic
        ↓
Zero downtime deployment

=========================================================
WHY COMPANIES USE ANSIBLE
=========================================================

- Idempotent (safe to run multiple times)
- Agentless (no agent installation required)
- Easy YAML syntax
- Works across Linux, Windows, Cloud
- Good for configuration consistency

=========================================================
ONE LINE SUMMARY
=========================================================

In production, Ansible is used to configure servers, deploy applications, manage services, enforce security, and automate infrastructure across multiple machines.


```
